<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-166-059 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 624 628</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  May 1991 v2 n5 p38(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Status of Windows in the corporate world. (Microsoft Corp.'sWindows 3.0 graphical user interface) (survey by ForresterResearch)(Forum)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Forrester Research Inc. (Surveys).andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (Business use).andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceSurveyStandardsBusiness PlanningCompaniesUser Needs.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Status of Windows adoption. (graph)Factors inhibiting the roll-out of Windows. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>STATUS OF WINDOWS IN THE CORPORATE WORLD Forty percent of the installed PCsin Fortune 1,000 firms will rely on Microsoft Windows 3.0 by the end of 1991,according to Forrester Research (Cambridge, MA), which surveyed 50 Fortune1,000 companies.andP;  The report concluded that Windows 3.0 will emerge as theindustry standard for the PC computing platform within the next year.andM;Of the Fortune 1,000 companies interviewed, only one had no plans to evaluateWindows 3.0.andP;  A full 43 percent already have Windows 3.0 and are just waitingfor Windows versions of major applications, such as Lotus 1-2-3, dBase, andWordPerfect, before implementing the upgrade.andP;  (See top chart.)andM;However, while many Fortune 1,000 companies are setting their sights onWindows 3.0, 49 percent of the surveyed firms said the cost of upgrading286-based systems with Windows--at least $1,000 per user--was the biggestfactor keeping them from making the upgrade, especially in the midst of arecession.andP;  (See bottom chart.)andO;</TEXT></DOC>